Just three nights of bad sleep is enough to dramatically reduce the body's ability to process glucose and raise the risk of diabetes, a study released Monday found.
Deep sleep, or "slow wave sleep," is considered the most restorative form of sleep and has been shown to be important for mental clarity.
For decades, I assumed I needed to sleep just five to six hours a night.
If you want to keep a healthy weight, sleep seven to eight hours a day and no more or less, scientists have discovered.
Loss of sleep, even for a few short hours during the night, can prompt one's immune system to turn against healthy tissue and organs, according to a recent study.
